This paper deals with the problem of channel simulation via interactive communication, which is a fundamental problem in information theory. The problem involves two-way communication links and shared common randomness, which are typical topics in the information theory subfield of communication theory (cs.IT). The paper also employs the technique of "output statistics of random binning," which is a method used in coding theory and information theory (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper deals with the generation of random variables, which is a topic in machine learning and signal processing (cs.MM). The paper also involves the study of tradeoff curves, which is a topic in optimization and game theory (cs.SI). Finally, the paper provides an exact computable characterization of the problem, which involves the use of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS).
